# Jahid _v_ Felizardo Paras Jose and others  

### \[2022\] SGDC 141

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">District Court Suit No 1008 of 2019</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">08 July 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">District Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Ng Tee Tze Allen</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Mr N Srinivasan and Ms Dakshayani (Hoh Law Corporation) for the plaintiff; First defendant in person; Mr Peter Ong, Mr Marcus Lim, and Ms Shamila Nair (Peter Ong Law Corporation) for the second defendant; Mr Christopher Fernandez and Ms Low Huai Pin (Tan Kok Quan Partnership) for the third defendant; Ms Sancia Ng and Ms Dorothy Tan (Tito Isaac &amp; Co) for the fourth defendant.</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Jahid — Felizardo Paras Jose — Zoe International Pte Ltd — Starbucks Coffee Singapore Pte Ltd — UOL Property Investments Pte Ltd</td></tr></tbody></table>

Tort – Negligence

Tort – Contributory negligence

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in HC/DCA 31/2022 and HC/DCA 32/2022.\]

8 July 2022 - Judgment reserved.

### District Judge Ng Tee Tze Allen:

## Introduction

1       This action concerns an accident that took place on 7 April 2018 at a Starbucks Coffee outlet located at 101 Thomson Road, #01-01 of United Square (the “**premises**”).

2       The plaintiff was a foreign worker assigned to carry out air-conditioning and mechanical ventilation installation and service works (the “**works**”). To reach the air conditioning units, he had to climb more than 3 metres[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1) up a concealed fixed ladder (the “**Ladder**”) to reach a platform above the false ceiling. He would then crouch and/or kneel on the platform to work. As the platform had jagged edges, the plaintiff would lay cardboard on it before working.

3       The plaintiff was carrying cardboard up the Ladder to the platform at the material time. He had positioned the cardboard at his neck between his right shoulder and head. He claimed to have lost his balance when he was close to the top of the ladder. He then fell and sustained injuries.

4       On 8 October 2019, the plaintiff started this action against the following defendants:

> (a)     The 1st defendant whom he worked as a freelance worker for.[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2) The 1st defendant was also the subcontractor for the works.[^3]

> (b)     The 2nd defendant who was the main contractor for the works.[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4)

> (c)     The 3rd defendant who had leased the premises and was operating a Starbucks Coffee outlet from it. The 3rd defendant was also the person who had erected the Ladder.[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5)

> (d)     The 4th defendant who was the landlord of the premises.[\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6) It had engaged the 2nd defendant as main contractor for the works.[^7]

5       All four defendants denied liability. They also claimed that the plaintiff was contributorily negligent and the author of his own misfortune.

6       At the end of trial on liability, I expressed my concern as to whether the 1st defendant would be able to prepare his submissions given that he was not represented. The 1st defendant said that he would get help. As such, I directed parties to file their closing and reply submissions. Notwithstanding, all parties save for the 1st defendant filed their submissions. Having heard the evidence and considered the submissions filed, I enter interlocutory judgment for the plaintiff against all four defendant to the extent of 70%. The grounds of my decision follow.

## Issues

7       The following issues arose for determination:

> (a)      **Issue 1:** What the proximate cause(s) for the plaintiff’s fall were.

> (b)      **Issue 2:** Whether any of the defendants was negligent.

> (c)      **Issue 3:** Assuming Issue 2 is answered in the affirmative, whether the plaintiff was contributorily negligent.

> (d)      **Issue 4:** Assuming Issue 3 is answered in the affirmative, how liability should be apportioned.

## Issue 1: What were the proximate cause(s) of the fall

### The parties’ cases

8       The plaintiff’s actions leading to the fall were captured by a CCTV. The CCTV footage showed the plaintiff picking up flattened cardboard boxes from the ground and placing them on his right shoulder. He is then seen climbing up the Ladder and out of the CCTV’s field of view. Shortly after, the plaintiff is seen again having fallen to the ground.[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8) It was not disputed that the plaintiff fell because he had lost his balance.[^9]

9       The plaintiff submitted that he fell because there was no fall restraint or fall arrest system (e.g. lifeline or a safety cage).[\[note: 10\]](#Ftn_10) According to the plaintiff, he had told the 1st defendant and the 4th defendant’s representative that the Ladder was dangerous during a pre-work survey in March 2018 about one month before the works in April 2018. However, he was told that the Ladder the only means of access, and as such, there was no choice but to use it. [^11]

10     The defendants accept that there was no fall restraint / arrest system at the time.[\[note: 12\]](#Ftn_12) They also did not take issue with the plaintiff’s use of the cardboard as part of his work. But they took issue with how the plaintiff climbed the Ladder with the cardboard. Their position was that the plaintiff should not have carried the cardboard whilst climbing the Ladder, and that by doing so, he had caused the fall. It was also their position that the plaintiff failed to maintain three-point contact whilst climbing the Ladder.[^13]

### My decision on what caused the fall

11     In my judgment, both the absence of a fall restraint/arrest system and the plaintiff’s attempt to climb the Ladder whilst carrying the cardboard led to the fall. I explain.

#### The absence of a fall arrest system

12     I start with the fall restraint / arrest system (e.g. lifelines or life cages). The 3rd defendant’s case was that it was a “speculative hypothetical scenario that the installation of a lifeline or safety cage could have prevented the Plaintiff from falling” for which no evidence was led.[\[note: 14\]](#Ftn_14)

13     I disagree.

14     First, the whole point of fall restraint / arrest systems is to prevent falls or reduce injuries. Thus, Regulation 2 of the Workplace Safety and Health (Work at Heights) Regulations 2013 (the “**WAH Regulations**”) defines a “fall arrest system” as a system “designed to prevent or reduce the severity of injury to a person in the event of a fall”.

15     For ladders which rises more than 3 metres, the WAH Regulations goes on further to provide at Regulation 18(10) that “there shall be provided a safety cage or other practicable measures to prevent fall of the person.” An image of one such safety cage is set out below:

![](data:image;base64,)

Figure 1[\[note: 15\]](#Ftn_15)

16     How such safety cages worked was explained in the plaintiff’s counsel’s cross examination of the 2nd defendant’s project manager, Mr Eugene Julien. Assuming the plaintiff lost his balance or footing after entering the safety cage, he would have been supported by the cage wall thereby reducing the risk of him falling to the ground:[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16)

> Q:    Now, if---for example, he’s in a safety cage inside and he were to fall, there’s a cage behind. You just---the backbone hits the cage that’s all, correct?

> A:    It’s possible, Sir.

17     As for lifelines, I thought that the 3rd defendant’s own actions were a testament to its efficacy. The 3rd defendant’s Ms Allison Neo stated in her AEIC that after the accident, the 3rd defendant had engaged a safety consulting firm, QE Safety Consultancy Pte Ltd (“**QE Safety**”), to assess and design safety and fall prevention measures for the Ladder. On QE Safety’s advice, a lifeline was installed at the Ladder in or around June 2018.[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17) Surely, the 3rd defendant would not have spent money to install a lifeline after the accident if they thought its efficacy was “speculative”. Photographs of the lifeline which the 3rd defendant installed after the accident are set out below:

![](data:image;base64,)

>> Figure 2[\[note: 18\]](#Ftn_18)

18     Under these circumstances, I accept that the presence of a fall arrest system could have prevented the plaintiff from falling even if he had lost his balance when climbing the Ladder.

#### Climbing the Ladder whilst carrying cardboard

19     I turn to the question of whether the plaintiff fell off the Ladder because he was carrying cardboard.

20     The plaintiff submitted that this was not the case. Accordingly, the cardboard was light and he could maintain three-point contact whilst carrying it.[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19)

21     I was unable to accept the plaintiff’s submission. The fact that carrying objects whilst climbing a ladder increases the risk of falling is self-evident. The plaintiff himself testified that he learnt during the Safety Work from Height course that he was not to carry anything when climbing ladders regardless of whether it was light or not.[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20) Furthermore, the cardboard which the plaintiff carried was not small.[^21] The plaintiff confirmed that he had picked up 3 cardboard boxes[^22] of about 2 feet by 2 feet each, which he folded in half.[^23] On this basis, the plaintiff would have been carrying multiple pieces of cardboard each measuring 1 feet by 2 feet. This would surely have impeded his ability to climb the Ladder safely. Indeed, the plaintiff himself admitted that it was dangerous for him to do so.[^24] For perspective, I reproduce below a screenshot of the CCTV footage showing the plaintiff with the cardboard:

![](data:image;base64,)

Fig 3[\[note: 25\]](#Ftn_25)

#### Conclusion

22     For the reasons above, I find that the absence of a fall arrest system and the plaintiff’s decision to carry the cardboard caused the accident. I turn to the question of which, if any, of the defendants should be held liable for the accident, before considering whether the plaintiff was contributorily negligent.

## Issue 2: Whether the defendants were negligent

### The law

23     The elements for the tort of negligence were not in dispute: (a) the defendant must owe the claimant a duty of care; (b) the defendant’s conduct must have breached the duty of care by falling below the requisite standard; (c) the claimant must have suffered loss; and (d) the defendant’s breach of duty must have been a cause of the claimant’s loss: _Miah Rasel v 5 Ways Engineering Services Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 3 SLR 480</span> (“**_Miah Rasel_**”) at \[26\].

24     To determine whether the first element (i.e. a duty of care) is established, the court applies the test set out in _Spandeck Engineering (S) Pte Ltd v Defence Science & Technology Agency_ <span class="citation">\[2007\] 4 SLR(R) 100</span> (“**_Spandeck_**”). Broadly, it must first be established that there is factual foreseeability. This refers to a reasonable foreseeability and will almost always be satisfied. Next, there must be sufficient legal proximity (including physical, circumstantial and causal proximity). If there is factual foreseeability and sufficient legal proximity, a _prima facie_ duty of care arises. The court will then consider if there are any policy considerations to negate the duty of care: _Spandeck_ at \[73\]-\[86\].

25     When ascertaining whether a duty of care exists (and if so, the appropriate standard), the Workplace Safety and Health Act (Cap 354A, 2009 Rev Ed) (“**WSHA**”), its accompanying regulations (collectively, the “**WSH Framework**”), and other guidelines are relevant because they set out the industry standards of care and practice: _Miah Rasel_ at \[27\]-\[30\].

### Whether the 1st defendant was negligent

26     It was undisputed that the plaintiff worked for the 1st defendant as a freelance worker and that the plaintiff took instructions from him for the works. The 1st defendant accepted in trial that he considered himself the plaintiff’s employer.[\[note: 26\]](#Ftn_26)

27     As such, there was little doubt that _Spandeck_ requirements were met such that the 1st defendant owed the plaintiff a duty of care. **First**, it is certainly foreseeable that there is risk of falling off the Ladder if precautionary measures were not taken. The regulatory framework which contains express provisions that guards against this risk makes this clear (see \[30\] below). **Second**, there is also a sufficiently proximate relationship between the plaintiff and the 1st defendant. In _Awang bin Dollah v Shun Shing Construction & Engineering Co Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[1997\] 2 SLR(R) 746</span> (“**_Awang bin Dollah_**”), it was held at \[20\]-\[24\] that a defendant would owe a claimant a duty of care as his employer if the defendant exercised control or had the right to exercise control in respect of the work which the claimant was engaged to do. **Third**, no policy considerations were identified to negate the duty of care.

28     The scope of the 1st defendant’s duty of care as the plaintiff’s _de facto_ employer is threefold: to provide a competent staff of men; adequate material; and a proper system of work and effective supervision: _Parno v SC Marine Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[1999\] 3 SLR(R) 377</span> (“**_Parno_**”) at \[45\]-\[48\]. For this case, the issue was whether a proper system of work was provided. This involves devising a suitable system and instructing his men in what they must do: _Parno_ at \[46\].

29     In my view, the 1st defendant failed to devise a suitable system of work or instruct his men in what they must do.

30     First, the 1st defendant testified that climbing the Ladder without any safety measures was dangerous.[\[note: 27\]](#Ftn_27) I agree:

> (a)     As noted at \[15\], the WAH Regulations provides at Regulation 18(10) that for ladders which rises more than 3 meters “there shall be provided a safety cage or other practicable measures to prevent fall of the person.” In the present case, it is undisputed that the Ladder was more than 3 meters (see \[2\] above). However, no safety cage or any other practicable measure to prevent falls was provided.

> (b)     The WSH Council’s Code of Practice for Working Safely at Heights (2013, 2nd Rev) further states that additional fall prevention measures shall be considered:

>> 11.3.2 For fixed ladders that rise a vertical distance of more than 3 metres, additional fall prevention measures shall be considered (e.g., installation of a safety cage shown in Fig 11.6).

>> 11.3.4 A risk assessment shall be conducted to determine if additional fall prevention measures associated with the use of fixed ladders are required (e.g., installation of a vertical life line).

31     Notwithstanding, the 1st defendant did little to ensure that fall prevention measures were put in place. The only thing he did was to suggest to the 4th defendant that they erect scaffolding or install a cage around the Ladder. But these suggestions were rejected and nothing more was done.[\[note: 28\]](#Ftn_28) Indeed, the 1st defendant did not even apply his mind when filling up the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form. Item 7 of the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form proposed as “Existing Risk Control(s)” for “Working at height” the use of “scaffolding” and a “safety harness with by-pass shock absorber”.[^29] However, the 1st defendant admitted that he intended to use neither and that he treated the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form as a “form filling exercise”:[^30]

> Q:    Yes, okay. So, things like safety harness with by-pass shock absorber to be hooked at all time is stated just above “Check and ensure that scaffolding is certified by scaffolds supervisor, even then, it is just in name because nobody uses the scaffold. Steve also goes up net---no, not scaffolders, the safety harness, right, safety harness. Steve also never use, you also never use, it was never intended to be used in any event, correct?

> A:    Correct, correct.

> Q:    Yes. Okay. And---so, if you were to look in this particular risk assessment, wherever it is stated to be a safety supervisor, right, in these pages, it was never meant to be Jahid at all, it’s just a form filling exercise, correct?

> A:    Correct, correct.

32     For completeness, the 1st defendant also testified during trial that he had subsequently studied the situation and space before concluding that the scaffolding was not necessary.[\[note: 31\]](#Ftn_31)

33     I do not accept this position. It may be the case that the using of scaffolding might not appropriate[\[note: 32\]](#Ftn_32) or the only way to access the platform safely. However, I did not think that this decision arose “subsequently” out of a “study” of the “situation \[and\] space”. The 1st defendant’s AEIC indicated that he gave up on using scaffolding during the pre-work survey itself,[^33] and not after the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form was submitted.

34     In any event, even if the 1st defendant conducted a subsequent “study”, nothing came of it. The only safety measure identified in his AEIC was the use of a harness. But even then, his evidence was that using it would compromise, and not improve, safety:[\[note: 34\]](#Ftn_34)

> 8.    I wish to state that for the site survey, I had climbed up the cat ladder carefully without using any harness. **I felt that using the harness was also not safe since it would be in breach of the 3-point contact rule**, as one hand would be required to actively hook and unhook the harness to different poles as one climbed up or down the ladder and the position changed.

> 9.    … To access the platform, we had to climb the cat ladder. **None of us used a harness. Harnesses were kept in the van.** The Plaintiff did not ask to use a harness; if he had wanted to use a harness, I would not have stopped him…

> (emphasis in bold)

35     Finally, there was also no evidence of the 1st defendant instructing the plaintiff on how to climb the Ladder safely.

36     Under these circumstances, I find the 1st defendant had breached his duty of care to the plaintiff.

### Whether the 2nd defendant was negligent

#### The 2nd defendant’s role

37     As there was some dispute as to the 2nd defendant’s role, I start with my views on the same.

38     I start with what the parties agreed on. The 2nd defendant was the project manager and main contractor for the works.[\[note: 35\]](#Ftn_35) It had appointed the 1st defendant as the sub-contractor for the works,[^36] approved the above-mentioned Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form,[^37] monitored the work schedule, work progress and supply of material, and updated the 4th defendant of the progress of the works.[^38]

39     I turn to what was disputed. In its submissions, the 2nd defendant characterised its role as one where it: (a) had no control or right to control the plaintiff in his work; (b) did not exercise any control or supervision over the plaintiff; and (c) did not have sufficient control over the worksite or the activities that took place.[\[note: 39\]](#Ftn_39) On this basis, the 2nd defendant submitted that it did not owe the plaintiff a duty of care. The plaintiff disagreed.

40     I did not accept the 2nd defendant’s limited characterisation of its role. Even if the 2nd defendant did not exercise control over the plaintiff, it certainly had the power to do so. The 2nd defendant’s Mr Eugene Julian was the “Manager” who “Approved” the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form.[\[note: 40\]](#Ftn_40) This meant that he had the power to accept or reject measures proposed to eliminate or mitigate risks. His evidence also made clear that this was not a pure administrative function. He admitted that he was supposed to review the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form,[^41] and consider the relevant rules, regulations, and code of practice.[^42]

41     Apart from approving the risk controls in the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form, Mr Eugene Julian also accepted that the 2nd defendant was responsible for ensuring that the “existing risk controls” were “actually implemented” at the worksite.[\[note: 43\]](#Ftn_43) Indeed, he gave a written undertaking on the 2nd defendant’s behalf to supervise the works and to ensure compliance with the WSHA. This undertaking is found in the 4th defendant’s Carry Out Work Permit which Mr Eugene Julian signed and affixed 2nd defendant’s company stamp to. The relevant portions of the Carry Out Work Permit read:[^44]

> UOL PROPERTY INVESTMENTS PTE LTD

> United Square

> Form C Carry Out Work Permit

> **…**

> Name of the Contractor: Zoe International Pte Ltd

> Person to contact: \[1st defendant\] Mobile Phone No: \[XXX\]

> Description of works:

> Dismantle and replace fands of FCU

> …

> 4.    I/We Zoe International Pte Ltd understand that I/We shall be present full-time to supervise the works and also ensure that the followings are complied with at all times:

>> …

>> (2)    Workplace Safety and Health Act

>> …

42     For completeness, Mr Eugene Julian also stated that he had discharged his duty by submitting the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form and having the 1st defendant supervise on its behalf.[\[note: 45\]](#Ftn_45) However, this relates to **_how_** the 2nd defendant carried out its role, and not **_what_** its role actually was. We are currently concerned with the latter, and here, Mr Eugene Julian admitted that as the main contractor, the 2nd defendant had to ensure the safety of both its and its sub-contractor’s workers:[^46]

> Q:    Okay. Okay. So, now, you have stated that, the very last line, “I did not have control over the Plaintiff’s conduct at work and the Plaintiff was not acting under mine or 2nd Defendant’s instruction.” My point is this, even if you say that you had no conversation with Mr. Jahid, you are the contractor, you can call yourself the main contractor. **Main contractors have duties to ensure the workers of the main contractors and sub-contractors’ workers, that their safety is paramount, must ensure it’s a safe place of work, and a safe system of work, correct?**

> **A:**      **Correct, Sir.**

> **Q:**      **And as a main contractor, you also have to ensure that if they were to climb the cat ladder, the cat ladder is safe for its use, correct?**

> **A:**      **Correct, Sir.**

> (emphasis in bold)

#### Whether the 2nd defendant owed the plaintiff a duty of care

43     Given the 2nd defendant’s role as set out above, I had little doubt that the _Spandeck_ requirements were met such that the 2nd defendant owed the plaintiff a duty of care.

44      **First**, it was certainly foreseeable to the 2nd defendant that a person such as the plaintiff may fall off the Ladder. The Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form expressly identified “worker fall from height” as a hazard of working at height.

45      **Second**, there is also sufficient proximity between the plaintiff and the 2nd defendant. As the Court of Appeal held in _Jurong Primewide Pte Ltd v Moh Seng Cranes Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] 2 SLR 360</span> (“**_Jurong Primewide_**”) at \[41\], “it would be very hard to think of situations where sufficient proximity to give rise to a common law duty of care will not be found to exist due to the control contractors … have over the worksite and the on-going activities on it.” This is because of “their well-placed abilities to foresee and be aware of the various possible mishaps that others without operational responsibilities and control may not be able to identify” and the potential that their negligence has “to result in fatal, or at least costly, consequences”.

46     In my view, the Court of Appeal’s observations apply wholly to the facts before us. Not only was the 2nd defendant responsible for approving the safety measures which the 1st defendant proposed in the Activity-Based Risk Assessment From, approving them, and ensuring that they are actually complied with (see \[37\]-\[42\] above), it was also responsible for ensuring compliance with the WSHA which focused on strengthening the safety management of worksites (see _Jurong Primewide_ at \[42\]) which I turn to.

47     I accept that the mere existence of a statutory duty is not conclusive of a common law duty. However, it is a strong factor pointing towards sufficient legal proximity. In this respect, and as the plaintiff submitted, the 2nd defendant was “a person who, in connection with any trade, business, profession or undertaking” had “engage\[d\] any other person” (i.e. the 1st defendant) “to supply labour or do work for gain or reward”. As such, it was a “principal” pursuant to WSHA Section 4(1) and owed the following statutory duties:

> (a)     the duty to take “so far as is reasonably practicable, such measures as are necessary to ensure that any contractor engaged by the principal … has taken adequate safety and health measures in respect of any machinery, equipment, plant, article or process used, or to be used, by the contractor or any employee employed by the contractor”: WSHA Section 14A(1)(b);

> (b)     the duty to ascertain that its contractor “has conducted a risk assessment in relation to the safety and health risks posed to any person who may be affected by the work for which the contractor is engaged by the principal to do”: WSHA Section 14A(3)(a);

> (c)     the duty to “conduct a risk assessment in relation to the safety and health risks posed to any person who may be affected by his undertaking in the workplace”: Regulation 3 of the Workplace Safety and Health (Risk Management) Regulations (the “**RM Regulations**”); and

> (d)     the duty to “take all reasonably practicable steps to eliminate any foreseeable risk to any person who may be affected by his undertaking in the workplace”: RM Regulations, Regulation 4.

48      **Third**, I was not convinced that any policy consideration applied to negate the imposition of a duty of care. To the contrary, the WSH Framework underscored the need to impose one.

#### Whether the 2nd defendant breached its duty of care

49     I find that the 2nd defendant breached its duty of care to the plaintiff.

50     Even though it was responsible for approving the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form, the 2nd defendant did not take any care when doing so. It gave little (if any) thought to the issue of safety when approving the measures set out in the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form. The 2nd defendant’s Mr Eugene Julian testified that he did not ask any questions or “think about” it. Instead, he treated it as a form filling exercise and simply forwarded it on the 4th defendant after receiving it from the 1st defendant:[\[note: 47\]](#Ftn_47)

> Q:    Okay. But as far as you’re concerned, you did the form filling exercise and forwarded this risk assessment, which starts from BA37 to BA48, correct?

> A:    Mr. Ding is the one who fill up, Sir.

> Q:    Sorry?

> A:    Mr. Ding.

> Q:    Okay. **So, according to you, Mr. Ding filled up that. So, you don’t question anything, you don’t ask anything, you don’t think about anything, you just forward to UOL.**

> A:     **Yes, Sir.** Because he’s the one who will do the installation, Sir,--

> Q:    Okay.

> A:    and he’s---he is the one who did the pre-site survey.

> (emphasis in bold)

51     I was also prepared to accept that the statutory duties set out in the WSH Framework (see \[47\] above) were indicative of the 2nd defendant’s standard of care. And in this respect, I did not think that this standard has been met. In essence, the 2nd defendant had sought to delegate all of its duties to the 1st defendant. In the 2nd defendant’s own words, “there was no evidence that any officer or representative of \[the 2nd defendant\] was at the Worksite at all material times and/or had exercised any control or supervision of the Worksite and its workers, particularly \[the plaintiff\]”.[\[note: 48\]](#Ftn_48) This is clearly insufficient given its role as elaborated at \[37\]-\[42\] above.

52     Finally, there was also little doubt that the 2nd defendant’s breach was a reason for the fall. Its lackadaisical attitude towards the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form and its statutory duties meant that it did not consider or ensure that fall prevention measures were implemented. This led to the plaintiff climbing the Ladder without the same and his eventual fall.

### Whether the 3rd defendant was negligent

53     The 3rd defendant was the tenant of the premises. It had leased the premises from the 4th defendant and was operating a Starbucks Coffee outlet from it. It had erected the Ladder.

54     The plaintiff submitted that the 3rd defendant owed him a duty of care as an occupier of the premises.

55     The 3rd defendant accepted that it was an occupier of the premises and that it owed the plaintiff a duty of care in that capacity.[\[note: 49\]](#Ftn_49) However, the 3rd defendant denied being in breach of that duty of care because: (a) it was not responsible for or involved in how the works were to be carried out, (b) it was not informed of the need of scaffolding or a cage, (c) the Ladder was not a concealed danger, and (d) the 1st defendant and the plaintiff chose to use the Ladder. [^50]

56     I accept that the 3rd defendant was not required to supervise the 1st defendant (or the plaintiff) to ensure that they were observing a safe system of work, and that no liability should attach to the 3rd defendant on this basis. I was also prepared to accept that, factually, the 3rd defendant was not told of the need for scaffolding or a cage.

57     However, I do not agree that the 3rd defendant was blameless.

58     As noted, the 3rd defendant accepted that it was an occupier of the premises. This means that it owed a duty to exercise reasonable care in respect of the safety of their property: _See Toh Siew Kee v Ho Ah Lam Ferrocement (Pte) Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 3 SLR 284</span> at \[80\], \[113\], \[132\].

59     In determining the 3rd defendant’s standard of care, the WSH Framework is relevant (see \[25\] above). In this respect, and to the extent that the platform is the “workplace”, WSHA Section 11(b) provides that “it is the duty of every occupier of any workplace to take, so far as is reasonably practicable, such measures to ensure that … all means of access to or egress from the workplace … are safe … whether or not the person is at work or is an employee of the occupier”. This does not change even if “workplace” refers to the premises from which Starbucks Coffee outlet is operated. Regulation 14 of the WAH Regulations imposes a similar duty in such an event:

> 14.    Where in a workplace any person is required to carry out any work at height —

>> (a)    in or on an elevated place from which the person could fall;

>> (b)    in the vicinity of an opening through which the person could fall;

>> (c)    in the vicinity of an edge over which the person could fall;

>> (d)    on a surface through which the person could fall; or

>> (e)    in any other place (whether above or below ground) from which the person could fall,

> it shall be **the duty of the occupier of the workplace to take, so far as is reasonably practicable, such measures as are necessary to ensure safe means of access to and egress from any area in the workplace referred to in paragraph (a), (b), (c), (d) or (e).**

> (emphasis in bold)

60     However, the Ladder was not a safe means to access to and egress from the platform. As it rose to more than 3 metres in height, Regulation 18(10) of the WAH Regulations mandated that the Ladder be provided with a safety cage or other practicable measures to prevent fall of the person (see \[2\] and \[15\] above). But no such measures were provided until after the accident (see \[17\] above). And here, Regulation 18(7) places the obligation of complying with Regulation 18(10) on the 3rd defendant as the occupier. Regulations 18(7) and 18(10) read:

> (7)    Where a fixed vertical ladder is used in a workplace, it shall be the duty of the occupier of the workplace to ensure that the requirements in paragraphs (8), (9) and (10) are complied with.

> …

> (10)  Where a fixed vertical ladder used by any person carrying out any work in a workplace rises a vertical distance of more than 3 metres, there shall be provided a safety cage or other practicable measures to prevent fall of the person.

61     Finally, even if the provisions above are disregarded, I had no doubt that the 3rd defendant had to ensure that the Ladder was safe given that it built the Ladder and had a direct say in its safety. Indeed, it is certainly not the case that the 3rd defendant did not know that persons in the plaintiff’s position would use the Ladder to access the air conditioning units. Ms Allison Neo admitted that the Ladder was to access the air conditioning units,[\[note: 51\]](#Ftn_51) and explained in her AEIC that the 3rd defendant’s own contractors used it for that purpose:[^52]

> 25.    The Ladder was primarily used by Starbuck’s contractors to access the air conditioning units on top of the false ceiling. To the best of my knowledge, the contractors appointed by Starbucks would only be responsible for maintenance and servicing works.

62     Under these circumstances, I did not think that the 3rd defendant’s point that it was not told that it needed to install a cage or a lifeline added much. Surely, the 3rd defendant bears the onus of taking reasonable care to ensure the structures that it built on its premises are safe. And if it is not aware what was needed, to either find out or engage a professional who did. Here, the 3rd defendant led no evidence that this was done.[\[note: 53\]](#Ftn_53)

63     I turn to the 3rd defendant’s point that the 1st defendant and the plaintiff used the Ladder despite knowing that it was unsafe. Perhaps. However, that goes towards the 1st defendant’s liability and the plaintiff’s possible contributory negligence. The point does not detract from the fact that the 3rd defendant was an occupier of the premises and that it had installed the Ladder. At the end of the day, the 3rd defendant had to take reasonable care to ensure that the Ladder was safe by providing a practical means of preventing falls. But it did not. And this was one reason that the plaintiff fell and sustained injuries.

64     For completeness, the plaintiff also alleged breach of WAH Regulations, Regulations 5 and 20. I did not think that he established that these provisions were breached.

65     Regulation 5(1) imposes a duty on the “occupier of every **workplace specified in the Schedule**, and in which work at height is carried out, to establish and implement a fall prevention plan.” In the present case, however, it was not clear that the premises was a “workplace” specified in the Schedule:

> (a)     As the premises was a Starbucks Coffee outlet, paragraphs 2 to 8 of the Schedule are ruled out. Paragraph 2 concerns shipyards. Paragraphs 3 and 5 to 8 concern various types of factories. And paragraph 4, broadly speaking, concerns “premises where bulk storage of toxic or flammable liquid is carried on”.

> (b)     While paragraph 1 of the Schedule which relates to “any worksite” appears broadly worded, “worksite” has a specific definition. Regulation 2 reads:

>> “worksite” means any premises where any building operation or works of engineering construction is or are being carried out, whether or not by or on behalf of the Government or a statutory body, and includes any line or siding (not forming part of a railway) which is used in connection with the building operation or works of engineering construction.

> In this respect, no explanation was given as to how the works in question constitute a building operation or work of engineering construction.

66     Regulation 20 imposes the duty to implement a permit-to-work system at factories. The premises, however, is a Starbucks Coffee outlet, not a factory:

> Implementation of permit-to-work system

> 20.—(1)    Before the carrying out of any hazardous work at height **at a factory**, it shall be the duty of the occupier of the factory to —

>> (a)    appoint a competent person for the hazardous work at height at the factory to carry out the duties of an authorised manager in accordance with this Part; and

>> (b)    appoint a competent person for the hazardous work at height at the factory to carry out the duties of a work-at-height safety assessor in accordance with this Part.

> (2)    Before and during the carrying out of any hazardous work at height **at a factory**, it shall be the duty of the occupier of the factory to ensure that a permit-to-work system in accordance with this Part is implemented for that hazardous work at height.

> (3)    The permit-to-work system referred to in paragraph (2) shall provide that —

>> (a)    the hazardous work at height is carried out with due regard to the safety and health of persons carrying out the work;

>> (b)    such persons are informed of the hazards associated with the hazardous work at height and the precautions they have to take; and

>> (c)    the necessary safety precautions are taken and enforced when the hazardous work at height is being carried out.

67     For the reasons above, I find the 3rd defendant negligent.

### Whether the 4th defendant was negligent

68     It is undisputed that the 4th defendant was the landlord of the premises. It was also the party who engaged the 2nd defendant for the works. Prior to the works, its Mr Steve attended the pre-work site survey where he showed the 1st defendant where the air conditioning units were and how to access them.[\[note: 54\]](#Ftn_54)

69     The plaintiff submitted that the 4th defendant owed it a duty of care, which it breached.

70     I accept these submissions.

71     First, the 4th defendant was a joint occupier of the premises. There was little doubt that the 4th defendant had control over access to the premises or the platform in question. Without its permission, neither the plaintiff nor the 1st defendant could enter the premises. Furthermore, this was not a case where the 4th defendant, as landlord, had no say when the Ladder was built in the premises:

> (a)     Clause 3.9 of the 3rd and 4th defendants’ tenancy agreement provided, _inter alia_, that the 3rd defendant “will not without the prior written consent of \[the 4th defendant\] make any alternation or addition in or to the Demised Premises”.[\[note: 55\]](#Ftn_55)

> (b)     The 4th defendant’s Ms. Tee Mee Lan also testified that it was likely that the 4th defendant received the drawings and was aware of the installation of the Ladder,[\[note: 56\]](#Ftn_56) and that usually, the 4th defendant would usually be satisfied with the safety of any structure before permitting it to be installed.[^57]

Under these circumstances, I was prepared to find that the 4th defendant had some level of control over the premises. Thus, like the 3rd defendant, the 4th defendant owed the plaintiff a duty of care as occupier, which it breached.

72     Second, the 4th defendant’s Mr Steve also gave instructions which led to the accident. It was the 1st defendant’s evidence that he considered the Ladder unsafe and proposed that scaffolding or a cage be put up during the pre-work survey.[\[note: 58\]](#Ftn_58) However, Mr Steve rejected the proposal and told him that the 4th defendant’s contractors had been using the Ladder and that the workers just had to be careful. As the 1st defendant stated in his AEIC:[^59]

> 7.    Before the commencement of the Works, I had a site survey and then held a meeting with the 4th Defendants, who were in charge of the building management. The Carrier 40LM-100 fan coil was to be installed at the ceiling of the premises, which was about 5m high, and accessible only by a cat ladder… **I had suggested to the 4th Defendants to put up scaffolding or install a cage around the cat ladder** as the 5m height was higher than the usual ceiling height of 2.8m to 3. **The 4th Defendants’ response was that it was not practical to have a scaffold and their own air-conditioning technicians had been using the cat ladder to access the platform for servicing without problems. Further, they said that STA workers just had to be careful in carrying out the works.**

> (emphasis in bold)

73     Crucially, the 4th defendant did not call any witness to rebut this point. Now, it may be the case that Mr Steve has left the 4th defendant’s employment,[\[note: 60\]](#Ftn_60) and may be unwilling to give evidence. However, the 4th defendant could have subpoenaed him if he remained in Singapore, and no evidence was placed before me to show any attempt to secure him as a witness. The 4th defendant also did not call Mr Steve’s reporting officer who continued to be employed by the 4th defendant as its witness.[^61] Instead, the 4th defendant called Ms Tee Mee Lan as its sole witness. Ms Tee, however, had no personal knowledge of works or the pre-work survey. She joined the 4th defendant on 25 February 2019. This is approximately 10 months after the accident on 7 April 2018 and 11 months after the pre-work survey in March 2018.[^62]

74     Under these circumstances, I accept the 1st defendant’s evidence that the 4th defendant’s Mr Steve had rejected the 1st defendant’s proposals and instructed the 1st defendant (and the plaintiff) to climb the Ladder despite being told of the risks.

75     On these facts, the _Spandeck_ requirements would be satisfied even if I leave aside the 4th defendant’s status as an occupier of the premises. **First**, it is certainly foreseeable to the 4th defendant that the 1st defendant’s workers (like the plaintiff) may fall from the Ladder. The risk was highlighted during the pre-work survey and Mr Steve had responded that the 1st defendant’s workers had “to be careful”.

76      **Second**, proximity is also made out given that the plaintiff had followed Mr Steve’s instructions to use the Ladder. In this respect, I also find that the 4th defendant was a principal pursuant to WSHA Section 4(1): the 4th defendant had, in connection with its business, engaged the 2nd defendant to supply labour or do work for gain or reward. As such, the 4th defendant had the duty to take, so far as is reasonably practicable, such measures as are necessary to ensure the safety and health of, amongst others, its subcontractor’s employees where these employees are working under the 4th defendant’s direction as to the manner in which the work is carried out. WSHA Section 14(1) and (2) state:

> Duties of principals

> 14.—(1)    Subject to subsection (2), it is the duty of every principal to take, so far as is reasonably practicable, such measures as are necessary to ensure the safety and health of —

>> (a)    any contractor engaged by the principal when at work;

>> (b)    any direct or indirect subcontractor engaged by such contractor when at work; and

>> (c)    any employee employed by such contractor or subcontractor when at work.

> (2)    The duty imposed on the principal in subsection (1) only applies where the contractor, subcontractor or employee mentioned in that subsection is working under the direction of the principal as to the manner in which the work is carried out.

> …

77      **Third**, there is no countervailing policy consideration to negate a duty of care. It certainly could not be said that liability is being cast too wide since the 4th defendant had taken it upon itself to reject proposals on safety and instruct the 1st defendant (and his workers) to use the Ladder.

78     I find also that the 4th defendant had breached its duty of care when it instructed the 1st defendant to use the Ladder without sufficient consideration to safety (see \[72\] above) and that this was a cause for the fall. Making generic comments that the 1st defendant’s workers had “to be careful” is insufficient to discharge this duty of care. It is also not helpful to the plaintiff who complied with the 4th defendant’s instructions to use the unsafe Ladder.

## Issue 3: Whether the plaintiff was contributorily negligent

79     The law on contributory negligence was not in dispute. It is encapsulated in Section 3(1) of the Contributory Negligence and Personal Injuries Act (Cap 54, 2002 Rev Ed) which provides for a partial defence by reducing the quantum of damages payable to a claimant who failed to take care of his own safety, thereby causing loss to himself:

> Apportionment of liability in case of contributory negligence

> 3.—(1)    Where any person suffers damage as the result partly of his own fault and partly of the fault of any other person or persons, a claim in respect of that damage shall not be defeated by reason of the fault of the person suffering the damage, but the damages recoverable in respect thereof shall be reduced to such extent as the court thinks just and equitable having regard to the claimant’s share in the responsibility for the damage.

80     As noted, the defendants’ position was that the plaintiff was contributorily negligent. They argued that the plaintiff knew the risks involved because he was a trained safety supervisor. Notwithstanding, he climbed the Ladder whilst carrying the cardboards, and this led to the accident.

81     The plaintiff disagreed. He submitted that mere carelessness or inattentiveness does not amount to contributorily negligence.[\[note: 63\]](#Ftn_63) He referred me to _Ramandeep Singh v TMS Alliances Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2016\] SGDC 14</span> (“**_Ramandeep Singh_**”) where a claimant who fell from a cat ladder whilst carrying a tin of paint was found _not_ to be contributorily negligent.

82     I was prepared to accept that mere carelessness or inattentiveness does amount to contributory negligence. However, I did not think that _Ramandeep Singh_ applied. In _Ramandeep Singh_, the defence of contributory negligence was premised on the defendants’ assertion that the claimant chose to carry the paint unsafely instead of using a wire rope that he was provided to lower it down. The court rejected the defendants’ assertion on the facts. It held at \[10\] that no such wire rope was provided. And as such, the claimant could not be held to be contributorily negligent for attempting to carry the tin of paint down whilst descending the cat ladder. In the present case, however, the plaintiff admitted there were safer alternatives that he could use.[\[note: 64\]](#Ftn_64) This included using the rope onsite to lift the cardboard,[^65] or waiting for his co-workers to assist him.[^66]

83     Furthermore, this was not a case where the plaintiff made a bad decision unknowingly. He was a trained safety supervisor who knew of the risks involved. In his AEIC, he stated that he had attended the pre-work survey and said that he found the “system of climbing up and down the cat ladder dangerous”.[\[note: 67\]](#Ftn_67) He also admitted in trial that he knew that he should not carry anything when climbing the Ladder,[^68] and that carrying the cardboard whilst climbing the Ladder was dangerous.[^69] Notwithstanding, he did not adopt the safer alternatives available to him and chose instead to carry the cardboard whilst climbing the Ladder.[^70]

84     Under these circumstances, I find the plaintiff to be contributorily negligent. He was aware that the situation was not safe from the start. However, instead of taking precautions, he made a bad situation even worse thereby contributing to the accident.

## Issue 4: How liability should be apportioned

### Preliminary issue

85     There is a preliminary issue. And that is whether I should apportion each defendant’s liability vis-à-vis the plaintiff. The plaintiff submitted I should not and that he is entitled to full judgement against all of the defendants. He referred me to the following passage in _Dingle v Associated Newspapers_ _<span class="citation">\[1961\] 2 QB 162</span>_ which was cited with approved in _Wong Jin Fah (suing by his next friend Ho Chia Hao) v L & M Prestressing Pte Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2001\] 3 SLR(R) 1</span> at \[89\]:

> **Where injury has been done to the plaintiff and the injury is indivisible, any tortfeasor whose act has been a proximate cause of the injury must compensate for the whole of it.** As between the plaintiff and the defendant, it is immaterial that there are others whose acts also have been a cause of the injury and it does not matter whether those others have or have not a good defence. These factors would be relevant in a claim between tortfeasors for contribution, but the plaintiff is not concerned with that; **he can obtain a judgment for total compensation from anyone whose acts has been a cause of his injury.** If there are more than one of such persons, it is immaterial to the plaintiff whether they are joint tortfeasors or not.

> (emphasis in bold)

86     I accept the principles above applied. Indeed, its correctness and applicability were not disputed by any of the defendants.

87     As such, subject to the issue of contributory negligence, I proceed on the basis that the plaintiff is entitled to a full judgment against all of the defendants.

### The parties’ extent of liability

88     When apportioning liability, the courts take into account, amongst other things, the “blameworthiness” of the parties involved. In this respect, the courts are, generally, more lenient to employees in cases of breach of statutory duty because statutes such as the Factories Act (or in the present case, the WHSA) exist to protect workmen from the consequences of their own carelessness: _Parno_ at \[63\]-\[64\]. These principles can be seen from the following cases.

89      _Xu Ren Li v Nakano Singapore (Pte) Ltd_ <span class="citation">\[2012\] 1 SLR 729</span> (“**_Xu Ren Li_**”) was an appeal against a decision of the District Court. The appellant was engaged by the respondent as a construction worker. The High Court held that the appellant was contributorily negligent. However, the evidence was insufficient to determine who was more at fault. As such, the High Court apportioned liability equally between the parties (see _Xu Ren Li_ at \[21\]).

90     In _Manickam Sankar v Selvaraj Madhavan (trading as MKN Construction & Engineering) and another_ <span class="citation">\[2012\] SGHC 99</span> (“**_Manickam Sankar_**”), the claimant placed his foot in a wrong place whilst crossing a catwalk. The Court found him contributorily negligent to the extent of one-third because he should have taken more care for his safety. In particular, the claimant should not have taken the risk of crossing even though he did not know how to secure his safety harness. That said, this was not a significant factor against him because he was a new worker and no steps were taken to ensure that all workers knew how to use their safety harnesses properly. In that case, poor lighting made it difficult to differentiate between the catwalk and the ceiling panels.

91     In _Miah Rasel_, the defendant had deployed the claimant and his supervisor to replace sprinkler pipes on the ceiling of a worksite. While replacing the sprinkler pipes, the claimant stepped out onto an air conditioning duct. It gave way and the claimant fell. The Court held as follows:

> (a)     The defendant was negligent because its supervisor had instructed the claimant to step onto the air conditioning duct (_Misah Rasel_ at \[20\]). He was also lackadaisical in adherence to its obligations under the WSHA and its accompanying regulations. The daily toolbox briefings were perfunctory affairs, and the defendant failed to provide adequately for the relevant personal protective equipment for working at height (_Misah Rasel_ at \[41\]).

> (b)     The claimant was found to be contributorily negligent. He was trained and sufficiently experienced to know the risk involved. He could have refrained from complying with the instructions and escalated the matter. However, he did not. He decided instead to undertake the risk (_Misah Rasel_ at \[23\]-\[24\], \[46\]).

On the above basis, the court found the claimant 25% contributorily negligent, and his employer 75% liable

92     In the present case, I was of the view that the defendants were more culpable than the plaintiff. Like the defendant in _Miah Rasel_, the defendants in the present case bore primary responsibility for safety but did little (if anything) to promote it:

> (a)     The 3rd and 4th defendants permitted the unsafe Ladder to be built and used in breach of Regulation 18(10) of the WAH Regulations (see \[58\]-\[63\] and \[71\]).

> (b)     When this issue was highlighted to the 4th defendant during the pre-work survey, it rejected the safety measures proposed by 1st defendant and maintained that the Ladder had to be used. There was no evidence that any regard was given to safety save for Mr Steve’s throwaway remark “to be careful” (see \[72\]-\[78\] above).

> (c)     Despite knowing the risks involved, the 1st defendant permitted the plaintiff to use the unsafe Ladder without doing anything to improve safety. He treated the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form as a form-filling exercise, gave little thought to mitigating the risks he had identified, and gave no instructions to improve safety (see \[29\]-\[35\] above).

> (d)     The 2nd defendant also took its responsibilities lightly. It was responsible for ensuring compliance with the WSHA and approving the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form. However, it approved the Activity-Based Risk Assessment Form blindly and did nothing to supervise the 1st defendant or ensure compliance with the WSHA (see \[37\]-\[52\] above).

93     That said, the plaintiff was also contributorily negligent. He was trained as a safety supervisor and knew that the Ladder was dangerous. Notwithstanding, he increased the risks posed to himself by carrying cardboard when climbing the Ladder even though safer alternatives were available (see \[82\]-\[84\] above). This made him more culpable than the claimant in _Miah Rasel_ who had simply followed his superior’s instructions.

94     Bearing the above in mind, I find the plaintiff 30% liable for the accident, and the defendants 70% liable.

## Conclusion

95     For the reasons above, I give interlocutory judgment for the plaintiff to the extent of 70% of the damages to be assessed. Issues relating to interest and costs are reserved to myself on a later date after the conclusion of the assessment of damages.
